    "body": "@marcinwyszynski \n\nReally thanks for that, it was really helpful!\n\nI was trying to have even smaller setup for these keys, and I was thinking that having only the server keys would be enough to achieve encryption. Do you think I'm losing anything with this only:\n\n```\nopenssl genrsa -passout pass:1111 -des3 -out server.key 4096\n\nopenssl req -passin pass:1111 -new -x509 -days 3650 -key server.key -out server.crt -subj '/C=US/ST=NY/L=NYC/O=MyApp/CN=grpc_server/emailAddress=support@myapp.com'\n\nopenssl rsa -passin pass:1111 -in server.key -out server.key\n```\n\nand the Ruby code would be:\n\nOn the server side:\n\n``` ruby\ncredentials = GRPC::Core::ServerCredentials.new(\n  nil, # pem_root_certs\n  [{\n    private_key: File.read('server.key'),\n    cert_chain: File.read('server.crt')\n  }],\n  true # force client authentication\n)\nserver = GRPC::RpcServer.new\nserver.add_http2_port('0.0.0.0:1983', credentials)\n```\n\nOn the client side:\n\n``` ruby\ncredentials = GRPC::Core::Credentials.new(File.read('server.crt'))\nclient = FortuneService::Stub.new('grpc_server:1983', creds: credentials)\n```\n"
